{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}
[[File:Hubert Pierlot and Robert Sturges.jpg|thumb|right|[[Hubert Pierlot]] ''(left)'', Prime Minister of the Government in Exile, April 1944.]]
The '''Belgian Government in London''' ({{lang-fr|links=no|Gouvernement belge <U+00E0> Londres}}, {{lang-nl|links=no|Belgische regering in Londen}}), also known as the '''Pierlot IV Government''', was the [[government in exile]] of [[Belgium]] between October 1940 and September 1944. After the invasion of Belgium by [[Nazi Germany]] in May 1940, the Belgian government, under Prime Minister [[Hubert Pierlot]], fled first to [[Bordeaux]] in [[French Third Republic|France]] and then to [[London]], where it established itself as the only legitimate representation of Belgium to the [[Allies (World War II)|Allies]]. Despite no longer having official authority in its own country, the government administered the [[Belgian Congo]] and held negotiations with other Allied powers about post-war reconstruction. It also exercised influence within the [[Free Belgian Forces|Belgian army-in-exile]] and attempted to maintain links with the [[Belgian Resistance|resistance in the occupied country]]. The government was [[tripartite]], involving ministers from the [[Catholic Party (Belgium)|Catholic]], [[Liberal Party (Belgium)|Liberal]] and [[Belgian Labour Party|Labour Parties]].

==Background==
{{main|Battle of Belgium}}
Politically, Belgian politics had been dominated in the interwar period by the [[Catholic Party (Belgium)|Catholic Party]], usually in coalition with the [[Belgian Labour Party]] (POB-BWP) or the [[Liberal Party (Belgium)|Liberal Party]]. The 1930s also saw the rise in popularity of Fascist parties within Belgium; most notably [[Rexism|Rex]] which peaked at the [[Belgian general election, 1936|1936 election]] with 11% of the vote.<ref>{{cite book|last=Bonney|first=Richard|title=Confronting the Nazi war on Christianity: the Kulturkampf Newsletters, 1936<U+2013>1939|year=2009|publisher=Peter Lang|location=Oxford|isbn=978-3-03911-904-2|pages=175<U+2013>6|coauthors=}}</ref> From the early 1930s, Belgian foreign and domestic policy had been dominated by the policy of neutrality; leaving international treaties and alliances and attempting to maintain good diplomatic relations with both [[British Empire|Britain]], France and Germany.{{cn|date = July 2013}}

Nevertheless, Belgium was invaded without warning by German forces on 10 May 1940. After [[Battle of Belgium|18 days of fighting]], the Belgian military surrendered on 28 May and the country was placed under the control of a German military government. Between 600,000<ref name=LS1>{{cite news|last=Bailly|first=Michel|title=Forces et faiblesses de l'arm<U+00E9>e belge en 1940 <U+00E0> la veille de la guerre|url=http://archives.lesoir.be/forces-et-faiblesses-de-l-armee-belge-en-1940-a-la-veil_t-19900202-Z02C79.html|accessdate=17 January 2013|newspaper=[[Le Soir]]|date=2 February 1990}}</ref> and 650,000<ref name=vdmeiren1>{{cite web|title=The Campaign of the Belgian army in May 1940|url=http://home.scarlet.be/vdmeiren/The%20Campaign%20of%20the%20Belgian%20army%20in%20May%201940.html|publisher=home.scarlet.be/vdmeiren|accessdate=17 January 2013}}</ref> Belgian men (nearly 20% of the country's male population)<ref name=woh1>{{cite web|title=Holland: The army and the interbellum|url=http://www.waroverholland.nl/index.php?page=holland-the-army-and-the-interbellum|publisher=Waroverholland.nl|accessdate=17 January 2013}}</ref> had been mobilized to fight. Most were made prisoners of war and detained in [[Stalag|camps]] in Germany.{{cn|date = July 2013}}

Unlike the [[Netherlands]] or [[Luxembourg]], whose monarchies went into exile alongside the government, King [[Leopold III of Belgium|Leopold III]] surrendered to the Germans alongside his army <U+2013> contrary to the advice of his government. In the days before his surrender, he allegedly attempted to form a new government under the pro-Nazi socialist [[Henri De Man]] though this was never realized.<ref name=Yapou1/> He remained a prisoner of the Germans, under house arrest, for the rest of the war.<ref name=Yapou1>{{cite book|last=Yapou|first=Eliezer|title=Governments in Exile, 1939<U+2013>1945|year=2006|location=Jerusalem|url=http://governmentsinexile.com/yapoubelgium.html|chapter=Belgium: Disintegration and Resurrection}}</ref>

==Establishment in London==
[[File:Eaton Square, London SW1W - geograph.org.uk - 1109683.jpg|thumb|The north side of [[Eaton Square]] in London where the government was established in 1940 and remained until September 1944.]]
While the government under Pierlot was still in Bordeaux, the Belgian Minister of Health, [[Marcel-Henri Jaspar]], arrived in London on 21 June. Jaspar believed that the Pierlot government intended to surrender to the Germans, and was determined to prevent it. Jaspar held talks with [[Charles De Gaulle]], and on 23 June gave a speech on [[British Broadcasting Corporation|BBC]] radio, in which he stated that he was personally forming an alternative government to continue the fight.<ref name=Yapou1/> His stance was condemned by the Pierlot government in Bordeaux, and he was received coldly by the Belgian ambassador in London, [[Emile de Cartier de Marchienne]].<ref name=Yapou1/> Jaspar, joined by the Socialist ''[[burgomaster]]'' of [[Antwerp]] [[Camille Huysmans]], along with other so-called "London Rebels" formed their own government on 5 July 1940.<ref name=Yapou1/> The British, however, were reluctant to recognize the Jaspar-Huysmans Government.<ref name=Yapou1/>

The challenge to the Pierlot government's authority spurred it into action.<ref name=Yapou1/> [[Albert de Vleeschauwer]], Pierlot's Minister of the Colonies, arrived in London on the same day as the Jaspar-Huysmans government was formed.<ref name=Yapou1/> As the only Belgian minister with legal power outside Belgium itself, De Vleeschauwer, together with [[Camille Gutt]] who arrived soon after, was able to form a temporary "Government of Two" with British approval in London, while they waited for [[Paul-Henri Spaak]] and Pierlot, who had been detained in [[Francoist Spain]] ''en route'' from France, to join them.<ref name=Yapou1/> Pierlot and Spaak reached London on 22 October 1940, marking the start of the period of the "Government of Four", providing the "official" government with great legitimacy.<ref name=Yapou1/>

The British were distrustful of many of the Belgian ministers, as well as the size and legitimacy of the government itself. However, with the arrival of the Prime Minister, it was reluctantly accepted:

{{cquote|The present Belgian government is a rump, but it is, as I understand it, a rump of unquestioned lineage, so to speak.|author=[[Alexander Cadogan]], [[Permanent Secretary|Permanent Under-Secretary]] at the British [[Foreign Office#The Foreign Office|Foreign Office]], December 1940<ref>FO 371/24277<U+2013>C13459, Cadogan minute, December 18, 1940</ref>|}}

The bulk of the Belgian government was installed in [[Eaton Square]] in the [[Belgravia]] area of London, which before the war had been the location of the Belgian Embassy. Other government departments were installed in nearby Hobart Place, [[Belgrave Square]] and [[Knightsbridge]].<ref name=Laporte1>{{cite news|last=Laporte|first=Christian|title=Quatre ans <U+00E0> Londres: Eaton Square, Petite Belgique|url=http://archives.lesoir.be/quatre-ans-a-londres-eaton-square-petite-belgique_t-19940901-Z08GC1.html|accessdate=7 July 2013|newspaper=[[Le Soir]]|date=1 September 1994}}</ref> The offices of the Belgian government were situated close to other governments-in-exile, including [[Luxembourgish government-in-exile|Luxembourg]], in [[Wilton Crescent]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome|url=http://londres.mae.lu/en/Welcome|publisher=Embassy of Luxembourg in London|accessdate=11 May 2013}}</ref> and [[Dutch government-in-exile|the Netherlands]] in [[Picadilly]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Plaque: Netherlands Government in exile|url=http://www.londonremembers.com/memorials/netherlands-government-in-exile|publisher=London Remembers|accessdate=6 May 2013}}</ref>

By December 1940, the British recognized the "government of four" as the legal representation of Belgium, with the same status as the other governments in exile:
{{cquote|[[Churchill war ministry|His Majesty's Government]] do regard the four Belgian ministers composing the Belgian Government in London as the legitimate and constitutional Government of Belgium and competent to exercise ''full authority'' in the name of the Sovereign State of Belgium.<ref name=Talmon130/>}}

==Composition==
Initially numbering just four ministers, the government was soon joined by numerous others. The government in exile comprised both politicians and civil servants in a number of government departments. Most were focused in the Ministries of the Colonies, Finance, Foreign Affairs and Defence, but with skeleton staff in a number of others.<ref name=Conway55-6/> By May 1941, there were nearly 750 people working in the government in London in all capacities.<ref name=Conway55-6>{{cite book|last=Conway|first=Martin|title=Europe in Exile: European Exile Communities in Britain 1940<U+2013>45|year=2001|publisher=Berghahn|location=New York|isbn=1571815031|pages=55<U+2013>6|edition=1st|coauthors=Gotovitch, Jos<U+00E9> (eds.)}}</ref>

