===Changes===
*19 February 1942
**[[Julius Hoste, Jr.|Julius Hoste]] (Liberal) becomes Undersecretary for Public Education.<ref name=comp/>
**[[Henri Rolin]] (POB-BWP) becomes Undersecretary for Defence.<ref name=Conway92/>
**[[Gustave Joassart]] (technical expert) becomes Undersecretary for Aid to Refugees, Labour and Social Welfare.<ref name=comp/>
*2 October 1942
**[[Antoine Delfosse]] (Catholic) becomes Minister for Justice, National Information and Propaganda.<ref name=comp>{{cite web|title=Le gouvernement Pierlot IV (1940<U+2013>1944)|url=http://www.histoire-des-belges.be/listes/les-gouvernements-de-la-belgique-unitaire/gouvernement-pierlot-iv-1940-1944|publisher=Histoire-des-belges.be|accessdate=14 July 2013}}</ref>
**[[Henri Rolin]] (POB-BWP) resigns as Undersecretary for Defence, in the aftermath of a minor mutiny in the Free Belgian forces.<ref name=Conway92>{{cite book|last=Conway|first=Martin|title=Europe in Exile: European Exile Communities in Britain 1940<U+2013>45|year=2001|publisher=Berghahn|location=New York|isbn=1571815031|page=92|edition=1st|coauthors=Gotovitch, Jos<U+00E9> (eds.)}}</ref> His role is assumed by Hubert Pierlot, who becomes Minister for National Defence in addition to his existing titles.<ref name=Conway92/>
*January 1943
**[[Arthur Vanderpoorten]] (Liberal), who had refused to follow the government to London, is apprehended by the Germans in France.<ref name=comp/> He would later die in [[Bergen-Belsen concentration camp]].
*3 May 1943
**[[August De Schryver]] becomes Minister for Interior Affairs and Agriculture, after having served as Minister without Portfolio.<ref name=comp/>
*6 April 1943
**[[August Balthazar]] (POB-BWP) becomes Minister for Public Works and Transport.<ref name=comp/>
*16 July 1943
**[[Gustave Joassart]] (technical expert) resigns as Undersecretary for Aid to Refugees, Labour and Social Welfare.<ref name=comp/>
*3 September 1943
**[[Joseph Bondas]] (POB-BWP) becomes Undersecretary for Aid to Refugees, Labour and Social Welfare.<ref name=comp/>
**[[Raoul Richard]] (technical expert) becomes Undersecretary for Supplies.<ref name=comp/>
*30 March 1943
**[[Paul Tschoffen]] (Catholic) becomes [[Minister of State (Belgium)|Minister of State]].<ref name=comp/>
*6 June 1944
**[[Paul Tschoffen]] (Catholic) becomes Head of the Mission for [[Civil Affairs]].<ref name=comp/>

==Role==
The Government in Exile was expected to fulfill the functions of a national government, but also represent Belgian interest to the Allied powers, leading [[Paul-Henri Spaak]] to comment that "all that remains of legal and free Belgium, all that is entitled to speak in her name, is in London".<ref>{{cite news|title=Why Belgium Fights On: Civilisation will Perish if Nazis Win|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/ndp/del/article/25851926|accessdate=7 May 2013|newspaper=[[The Mercury (Hobart){{!}}The Mercury]]|date=13 March 1941}}</ref>

===Belgian refugees===
One of the most pressing concerns facing the government in exile in 1940 was the situation of Belgian refugees in the United Kingdom. By 1940, at least 15,000 Belgian civilians had arrived in the United Kingdom, many of them without their possessions.<ref name=Conway61/> The refugees had originally been dealt with by the British government, however in September 1940, the government established a Central Service of Refugees to provide material assistance and employment for Belgians in Britain.<ref name=Conway57-8>{{cite book|last=Conway|first=Martin|title=Europe in Exile: European Exile Communities in Britain 1940<U+2013>45|year=2001|publisher=Berghahn|location=New York|isbn=1571815031|pages=57<U+2013>8|edition=1st|coauthors=Gotovitch, Jos<U+00E9> (eds.)}}</ref>

The British public was exceptionally hostile to Belgian refugees in 1940, because of the belief that Belgium had betrayed the Allies in 1940.<ref name=church1>{{cite web|last=Langworth|first=Richard M.|title=Feeding the Crocodile: Was Leopold Guilty?|url=http://www.winstonchurchill.org/support/the-churchill-centre/publications/finest-hour/issues-109-to-144/no-138/898-feeding-the-crocodile-was-leopold-guilty|publisher=Churchill Centre|accessdate=17 January 2013}}</ref> A British [[Mass Observation]] report noted a "growing feeling against Belgian refugees" in the United Kingdom,<ref>{{cite book|last=Crang, Jeremy A.|first=Addison, Paul|title=Listening to Britain: Home Intelligence Reports on Britain's Finest Hour, May<U+2013>September 1940|year=2011|publisher=Vintage|location=London|isbn=0099548747|pages=71; 56}}</ref> closely linked to Leopold's decision to surrender.<ref>{{cite book|last=Conway|first=Martin|title=Europe in Exile: European Exile Communities in Britain 1940<U+2013>45|year=2001|publisher=Berghahn|location=New York|isbn=1571815031|page=54|edition=1st|coauthors=Gotovitch, Jos<U+00E9> (eds.)}}</ref>

The government was also involved in the provision of social, educational and cultural institutions to Belgian refugees. In 1942, the government sponsored the creation of the [[Anglo-Belgian Club|Belgian Institute]] in London to entertain the Belgian refugee community in London.<ref name=Conway55-6/> By 1943, there were also four Belgian schools in Britain with 330 pupils between them, in [[Penrith, Cumbria|Penrith]], [[Braemar]], [[Kingston upon Thames|Kingston]] and [[Buxton]].<ref name=Conway60>{{cite book|last=Conway|first=Martin|title=Europe in Exile: European Exile Communities in Britain 1940<U+2013>45|year=2001|publisher=Berghahn|location=New York|isbn=1571815031|page=60|edition=1st|coauthors=Gotovitch, Jos<U+00E9> (eds.)}}</ref>

===Free Belgian forces===
[[File:United Nations Day Parade, London, 14 June 1943 TR1113.jpg|170px|thumb|[[Victor van Strydonck de Burkel]] in London, 1943. Van Strydonck had been made [[Baron]] for leading [[Charge of Burkel|a cavalry charge]] in 1918.]]
{{main|Free Belgian Forces}}
In a broadcast on French Radio, shortly after the Belgian surrender, Pierlot called for the creation of an army-in-exile to continue the fight:

{{cquote|With the same youthful courage that responded to the government's call, reunited with the elements of the Belgian military in France and Great Britain, a new army will be levied and organized. It will go into the line alongside those of our allies&nbsp;... all the forces we have will be put at the service of the cause which has become ours&nbsp;... It is important to assure immediately and in a tangible way, the solidarity which continues to unite the powers which have given us their support&nbsp;... |author=Pierlot's speech on French Radio, 28 May 1940<ref>{{cite book|last=Gerard, Emmanuel; Van Nieuwenhuyse, Karel (eds.)|first=|title=Scripta Politica: Politieke Geschiedenis van Belgi<U+00EB> in Documenten, 1918<U+2013>2008|year=2010|publisher=Acco|location=Leuven|isbn=978-90-334-8039-3|edition=2nd|pages=164<U+2013>5}}</ref>|}}

With some Belgian troops rescued from [[Dunkirk]] during [[Operation Dynamo]], as well as Belgian <U+00E9>migr<U+00E9>s already living in England, the government-in-exile approved the creation of an "Belgian Military Camp for Regrouping" (CMBR) in [[Tenby]], Wales.<ref name=BP1/> By July 1940, the camp numbered 462 Belgians, rising to nearly 700 by August 1940.<ref name=BP1>{{cite web|title=La Brigade Piron: Cr<U+00E9>ation en Grande-Bretagne|url=http://www.brigade-piron.be/creation_fr.html|publisher=Brigade-piron.be|accessdate=1 July 2013}}</ref> These soldiers were organized into the 1st Fusilier Battalion in August, and the government appointed Lieutenant-Generals [[Raoul Daufresne de la Chevalerie]] as commander, and [[Victor van Strydonck de Burkel]] as inspector-general of the new force.<ref name=Thomas15-6>{{cite book|last=Thomas|first=Nigel|title=Foreign Volunteers of the Allied Forces, 1939<U+2013>45|year=1991|publisher=Osprey|location=London|isbn=978-1-85532-136-6|pages=15<U+2013>6}}</ref> The government was later able to successfully lobby for the creation of a Belgian Section within the [[Royal Navy]], as well as the creation of two all-Belgian squadrons within the [[Royal Air Force]].

For the first years of the war, a degree of tension existed between the government and the army, which divided its allegiance between government and king. The Free Belgian forces, particular the infantry who had been training since 1940, held the government responsible for not being allowed to fight. In November 1942, 12 Belgian soldiers mutinied, complaining about their inactivity.<ref name=Conway92/> By 1943, the army's royalist stance had been moderated, allowing the government to re-gain the support of the military.<ref name=Conway94>{{cite book|last=Conway|first=Martin|title=Europe in Exile: European Exile Communities in Britain 1940<U+2013>45|year=2001|publisher=Berghahn|location=New York|isbn=1571815031|page=94|edition=1st|coauthors=Gotovitch, Jos<U+00E9> (eds.)}}</ref>

===Treaties and negotiations===
[[File:Original United Nations.jpg|175px|thumb|right|Poster depicting the flags of the "United Nations", including Belgium, that signed the [[Declaration by United Nations|Declaration of 1942]].]]
In September 1941, the Belgian government signed the [[Atlantic Charter]] in London alongside other governments in exile, presenting the common goals which the Allies sought to achieve after the war.<ref>{{cite web|title=Inter-Allied Council Statement on the Principles of the Atlantic Charter: September 24, 1941 [Text]|url=http://avalon.law.yale.edu/wwii/interall.asp|publisher=[[Yale University]]|accessdate=13 July 2013}}</ref> A year later, the government signed the [[Declaration by United Nations]] in January 1942, with 26 other nations, which would set a precedent for the foundation of the [[United Nations|United Nations Organisation]] in 1945.<ref>{{cite web|title=Declaration by the United Nations, January 1, 1942 [Text]|url=http://avalon.law.yale.edu/20th_century/decade03.asp|publisher=[[Yale University]]|accessdate=13 July 2013}}</ref>

From 1944, the Allies became increasingly concerned with laying the framework of post-war Europe. These were formalized through numerous treaties and agreements from 1944. In July 1944, Camille Gutt attended the [[Bretton Woods Conference]] in the United States on behalf of the Belgian government, establishing the [[Bretton Woods System]] of currency controls. During the negotiations, Gutt served as an important intermediary between the delegates of the major Allied powers.<ref>{{cite book|last=Crombois|first=Jean F.|title=Camille Gutt and Postwar International Finance|year=2011|publisher=Pickering & Chatto|location=London|isbn=9781848930582|page=107}}</ref> Through the agreements, the Belgian Franc's exchange rate would be tied to the [[United States Dollar|American Dollar]] after the war, while he conference also established the [[International Monetary Fund]] (IMF) of which Gutt would serve as the first director.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Bretton Woods Institutions|url=http://www.nbbmuseum.be/doc/infosheets/fiche_information_EN_19.pdf|format=PDF|publisher=[[National Bank of Belgium]]|accessdate=13 July 2013}}</ref>

In September 1944, the Belgian, the Netherlands and Luxembourgish governments in exile began formulating an agreement over the creation of a [[Benelux|Benelux Customs Union]].<ref name=Walsh1>{{cite news|last=Walsh|first=Jeremy|title=Benelux Economic Union <U+2013> A New Role for the 21st Century|url=http://martindale.cc.lehigh.edu/sites/martindale.cc.lehigh.edu/files/BeneluxEconomy.pdf|accessdate=13 July 2013|newspaper=[[Lehigh University]]}}</ref> The agreement was signed in the [[London Customs Convention]] on 5 September 1944, just days before the Belgian government returned to [[Brussels]] after the liberation.<ref>{{cite web|title=Treaty Establishing the Benelux Economic Union (1958)|url=http://www.cris.unu.edu/riks/web/treaties/Benelux.pdf|publisher=[[United Nations University]]|accessdate=13 July 2013}}</ref> The Benelux Customs Union was a major extension of [[Belgium<U+2013>Luxembourg Economic Union|a pre-war union]] between Belgium and Luxembourg, and would later form the basis of the ''Benelux Economic Union'' from 1958.<ref name=Walsh1/>

==Authority==
Unlike many other governments in exile, which were forced to rely exclusively on financial support from the Allies, the Belgian government in exile could fund itself independently. In large part, this was due to the Belgian national gold reserves, which had been moved to Britain, and provided an important asset.<ref name=Buyst>{{cite news|last=Erik|first=Buyst|title=Camille Gutt and Postwar International Finance|url=http://eh.net/book_reviews/camille-gutt-and-postwar-international-finance|accessdate=13 July 2013|newspaper=EH.Net|date=November 2011}}</ref> The Belgian government was also in control of the [[Belgian Congo]], which exported large amounts of raw materials (including [[Natural rubber|rubber]], [[gold]] and [[uranium]]) which the Allies relied on for the war effort.<ref name=Buyst/>

==Stances==
===Relations with Leopold III===
{{see also|Leopold III of Belgium}}
Despite being a constitutional monarch, the King of the Belgians had occupied an important political role within Belgium before the war. The decision of Leopold III to surrender to the Germans <U+2013> without consulting his own ministers <U+2013> outraged the Belgian cabinet.<ref name=Yapou1/> The King's apparent opposition to it undermined its credibility and legitimacy. For the first years of the war, the King was viewed as an alternative source of "government" by many, including figures in the Free Belgian military, which served to further undermine the official government in London. Later in the war, the government changed its position to be less belligerent towards the king.<ref name=Yapou1/> Belgian propaganda of the time instead emphasized the King's position as "martyr" and prisoner-of-war and presented him as sharing the same sufferings as the occupied country.<ref name=Yapou1/>

According to the [[Constitution of Belgium|Constitution of 1831]], the Belgian government was allowed to override the wishes of the King if he had been declared incompetent to reign.<ref name=Talmon150-1/> On 28 May 1940, the Pierlot government in France had declared the King to be under the power of the invaders and unfit to reign, providing strong legal foundations and making itself the only official source of government.<ref name=Talmon150-1>{{cite book|last=Talmon|first=Stefan|title=Recognition of Governments in International Law, with particular reference to Governments in Exile|year=2001|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|isbn=9780199248391|pages=150<U+2013>1|edition=Reprint.}}</ref> Although the King was technically the only person able to receive diplomatic legations and conclude treaties, the government in exile was able to do both during the war independently.<ref name=Talmon130>{{cite book|last=Talmon|first=Stefan|title=Recognition of Governments in International Law, with particular reference to Governments in Exile|year=2001|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|isbn=9780199248391|page=130|edition=Reprint.}}</ref>

===Relations with the Resistance===
[[File:Royal Air Force Bomber Command, 1942-1945. CL3987.jpg|thumb|Supplies for the Resistance dropped by British aircraft in the countryside north of [[Brussels]].]]
{{see also|Belgian Resistance}}
The Belgian government of Jaspar-Huysmans called for the creation of organized resistance in occupied Belgium from London, even before the [[Battle of France#Surrender and armistice|French surrender]]:

{{cquote|We trust fully in the power of Britain to deliver us from German bondage&nbsp;... We claim the right to share in the burden and honour of this fight in the measure of our modest, but not altogether negligible, resources. We are not defeatists&nbsp;...|author=Huysmans in radio broadcast, 23 June 1940<ref name=Yapou1>{{cite book|last=Yapou|first=Elizer|title=Governments in Exile, 1939<U+2013>1945|year=1998|location=Jerusalem|url=http://governmentsinexile.com/yapoubelgium.html|chapter=4: Belgium: Disintegration and Resurection}}</ref>}}

The government succeeded in obtaining control over British French-language radio broadcasts, {{lang|fr|''Radio Belgique''}}, to occupied Belgium. The radio station was essential for keeping the resistance and public alike informed, and was placed under the control of [[Paul M. G. L<U+00E9>vy|Paul L<U+00E9>vy]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Grosbois|first=Thierry|title=Pierlot, 1930<U+2013>1950|year=1998|location=Brussels|publisher=Racine|isbn=2873864850|pages=184<U+2013>7}}</ref> Amongst those working in the radio was [[Victor de Laveleye]], a former Belgian Minister who served as an announcer, who is credited for inventing the "[[V sign#The V for Victory campaign and the victory-freedom sign|V for Victory]]" campaign.<ref>{{cite web|title=V-Campaign|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20050312223729/http://home.luna.nl/~arjan-muil/radio/history/ww-2/v-campaign.html|publisher=Virtual Radio Museum|accessdate=6 May 2013}}</ref>

Nevertheless, the apparent isolation of the government-in-exile from the day-to-day situation in Belgium meant that it was viewed with suspicion by many resistance groups, particularly those whose politics different from the established government. The government, for its part, was afraid that resistance groups would turn into ungovernable political militias after liberation, challenging the government's position and threatening political stability.<ref>{{cite book|last=Moore|first=Bob (ed.)|title=Resistance in Western Europe|year=2000|publisher=Berg|location=Oxford|isbn=1-85973-274-7|page=54|edition=1st}}</ref> Nevertheless, the resistance was frequently reliant on finance and drops of equipment and supplies which both the government-in-exile and the British [[Special Operations Executive]] (SOE) were able to provide.<ref name=DeVidts89-90>{{cite journal|last=De Vidts|first=Kim|title=Belgium: A Small but Significant Resistance Force during World War II|journal=MA Thesis|url=http://www.hpu.edu/CHSS/History/GraduateDegree/MADMSTheses/files/2004KimdeVidts.pdf|format=PDF|year=2004|pages=89<U+2013>90|location=Hawaii Pacific University}}</ref> During the course of the war, the government-in-exile delivered between 124<U+2013>245 million [[Belgian Franc|francs]], dropped by parachute or transferred via bank accounts in [[Portugal in World War II|neutral Portugal]], to the {{lang|fr|''[[Arm<U+00E9>e secr<U+00E8>te (Belgium)|Arm<U+00E9>e Secr<U+00E8>te]]''}} group alone, with smaller sums also distributed to other organisations.<ref name=DeVidts89-90/>

In the early years of the war, contact with the government exile was difficult to establish. The {{lang|fr|''[[L<U+00E9>gion Belge (resistance)|L<U+00E9>gion Belge]]''}} dispatched a member to try to establish contact in May 1941, it took a full year to reach London.<ref name=DeVidts89-90/> Radio contact was briefly established in late 1941, however, the contact was extremely intermittent between 1942 and 1943, with a permanent radio connection to the {{lang|fr|''Arm<U+00E9>e Secr<U+00E8>te''}} (codenamed "Stanley") only established in 1944.<ref name=DeVidts89-90/>

In May 1944, the government-in-exile attempted to rebuild its relationship with the resistance by establishing a "Coordination Committee" of representatives of the major groups, including the ''L<U+00E9>gion Belge'', ''[[Belgian National Movement|Mouvement National Belge]]'', ''[[Groupe G]]'' and the ''[[Front de l'Ind<U+00E9>pendance]]''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Moore|first=Bob (ed.)|title=Resistance in Western Europe|year=2000|publisher=Berg|location=Oxford|isbn=1-85973-274-7|page=53|edition=1st}}</ref> However, the committee was rendered redundant by the liberation in September.

==Return to Belgium==
Allied troops entered Belgium on 1 September 1944.<ref name=Brussels1>{{cite web|title=1944: the Liberation of Brussels|url=http://www.brussels.be/artdet.cfm/5562|publisher=Brussels.be|accessdate=13 July 2013}}</ref> On 6 September, the [[Welsh Guards]] liberated the capital, [[Brussels]].<ref name=Brussels1/> The government in exile returned to Brussels on 8 September 1944.<ref name=Conway61>{{cite book|last=Conway|first=Martin|title=Europe in Exile: European Exile Communities in Britain 1940<U+2013>45|year=2001|publisher=Berghahn|location=New York|isbn=1571815031|page=61|edition=1st|coauthors=Gotovitch, Jos<U+00E9> (eds.)}}</ref> "Operation Gutt", a plan devised by Camille Gutt to avoid rampant inflation in occupied Belgium by limiting the money supply, was put into action.<ref>{{cite news|last=Marc|first=Metdepenningen|title=L'Op<U+00E9>ration Gutt <U+00E9>tait pretre en 1943|url=http://archives.lesoir.be/l-operation-gutt-etait-pretre-en-1943_t-19940910-Z08HG2.html|accessdate=14 July 2013|newspaper=[[Le Soir]]|date=10 September 1994}}</ref>

On 26 September, Pierlot formed a new government of [[National unity government|national unity]] (Pierlot V) in Brussels. The new government included many of the ministers (including all of the "four") from London, but for the first time also including the [[Communist Party of Belgium|Communists]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Le gouvernement Pierlot V (1944)|url=http://www.histoire-des-belges.be/listes/les-gouvernements-de-la-belgique-unitaire/gouvernement-pierlot-v-1944|publisher=Histoire-des-belges.be|accessdate=14 July 2013}}</ref> In December 1944, a new triparate government was formed, with Pierlot still as Prime Minister. In 1945, having been Prime Minister since 1939, Pierlot was finally replaced by [[Achille Van Acker]].

The government in exile was one of the last governments in which the traditional parties which had dominated Belgium since its creation were still present. In 1945, the POB-BWP changed its name to the [[Belgian Socialist Party]] (PSB-BSP) and the Catholic Party became the [[Christian Social Party (Belgium, defunct)|Christian Social Party]] (PSC-CVP).

